narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: This course introduced me to the primatological literature, which I was not familiar with. I developed new insights into the ways in which primatological research can contribute to the study of human origins and evolution.
I gained insights into key Primatological literature and theory that will be critical for my dissertation and future career.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The strengths of this course include: a solid body of literature, plenty of discussions and active engagement, interesting topics, the use of video materials, good feedback on the assignments. I do not have suggestions for possible improvements.

Strengths: Student engagement in material, well lead discussion by the Professor, material that spanned student interests, a variety of mediums to convey material, insightful and helpful feedback on assignments. Weaknesses: I thoroughly enjoyed this course and will take courses with this Professor in the future, as they are offered. I do not have suggestions for improvement at this time.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would absolutely recommend this course to other students interested in primatology, human evolution or both. The course is reading-heavy, so it's necessary to make adequate time to engage with the materials!

Yes, I would highly recommend this course to students interested in primates or evolution. This is a key course for students interested in pursuing a career in Biological Anthropology, and if students were interested in gaining a wide breadth of Biological Anthropology, but were not necessarily interested in primates, I would still recommend the course.
Yes. Great weekly topics and interesting readings. Professor Watts is incredibly knowledgeable and has amazing stories.
